Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Davenport","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): habitational name from a place in Cheshire named Davenport, from the Dane river (apparently named with a Celtic cognate of Middle Welsh <i>dafnu</i> ‘to drop, to trickle’) + Old English <i>port</i> ‘market town’.","Irish: in Tipperary, this is an English surname adopted by bearers of Munster Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donndubhartach</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>artach</i> ‘nobleman’.","History: John Davenport (died 1670) arrived in Boston, MA, in 1637. He came of an English Cheshire family associated with Capesthorne Hall, near Macclesfield."],"variants":[{"name":"Devenport","meanings":["English and Irish (Lancashire): variant of   Davenport  . The spelling <b>Devonport</b> is found in Ireland and it may have been this form which gave rise to <i>Devenport</i>."]},{"name":"Dunworth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamon, Niall.","Irish: adopted in Ireland by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> (see   Davenport   2).","English: perhaps a variant of <b>Dungworth</b>, see   Dunsworth  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Davenport was born in 1398, in Bramhall, Cheshire, England, his father, Sir Robert de Davenport I, was 33 and his mother, Joan Assheton, was 21. He married Agnes Alice Fitton in 1418, in Gawsworth, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1435, in Stockport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 37, and was buried in Stockport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1398–1435":"1398–1435","1404–1447":"1404–1447","1404–Male":"1404–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1410–1443":"1410–1443","1398–1478":"1398–1478","1419–1463":"1419–1463","1419–1478":"1419–1478","1423–Male":"1423–Surnud","1365–1436":"1365–1436","1377–1443":"1377–1443","3 May 1419":"3. mai 1419","1404":"1404","1436":"1436","1447":"1447","1435":"1435","1423":"1423","1478":"1478","1377":"1377","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1398":"1398","1365":"1365","1463":"1463","14 March 1397":"14. märts 1397","1419":"1419","1418":"1418","1405":"1405","Bramhall, Cheshire, England":"Bramhall, Cheshire, England","Stockport, Cheshire, England":"Stockport, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gawsworth, Cheshire, England":"Gawsworth, Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1398–1435":"1398–1435","1404–1447":"1404–1447","1404–Male":"1404–Kuo